([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n|website       = {{url|https://wilson.house.gov|House website}}\n}}\n'''Frederica Smith Wilson''' (born '''Frederica Patricia Smith'''; November 5, 1942) is a politician who has been a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] since 2011. Located in South [[Florida]], Wilson's congressional district\u2014numbered the [[Florida's 17th congressional district|17th]] during her first two years in Congress, and the [[Florida's 24th congressional district|24th]] since 2013\u2014is a majority African-American district that includes the southern parts of [[Broward County, Florida|Broward County]] and the eastern parts of [[Miami-Dade County, Florida|Miami-Dade County]]. Included within the district are Opa-locka, Hollywood, Miramar, and North Miami. She gained national attention in early 2012 as a result of her high-profile comments on the death of [[Trayvon Martin]].<ref name=\"wilson1\">{{cite web\n | url = https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-florida-shooting-congress/democratic-lawmakers-blast-police-in-teen-killing-idUSBRE82Q0W520120328\n | title = Democratic lawmakers blast police in teen killing\n | last = Smith\n | first = Donna\n | date = March 27, 2012\n | website = [[Reuters]]\n | publisher =\n | access-date = 2017-10-19}}</ref><ref name=\"wilson2\">{{cite web\n | url = http://www.cnn.com/2012/03/27/justice/florida-teen-shooting/index.html\n | title = Focus in Trayvon Martin case shifts to Washington\n | last =\n | first =\n | date = March 27, 2012\n | website = [[CNN]]\n | publisher =\n | access-date = 2017-10-19}}</ref>\n\nWilson is a member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]].<ref name=\"Congressional Bio\">{{cite web|title=Congresswoman Frederica S. Wilson: Biography |url=http://wilson.house.gov/about/full-biography |publisher=United States House of Representatives. wilson.house.gov |access-date=January 6, 2017 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207100039/https://wilson.house.gov/about/full-biography |archivedate=December 7, 2016 |df= }}</ref> The seat she was elected to became available when the incumbent [[Kendrick Meek]] ran for a seat in the Senate in 2010.\n\nWilson is known for her large and colorful hats, of which she owns several hundred. She has gone through efforts to get Congress to lift its ban on head coverings during House sessions, which dates back to 1837.<ref name = Politifact>{{cite web|last=Sherman|first=Amy|date=November 19, 2010|title=Congresswoman-elect Frederica Wilson says hat ban started in 1800s but can be waived|url=http://www.politifact.com/florida/statements/2010/nov/19/frederica-wilson/congresswoman-elect-wilson-says-hat-ban-started-18/|work=Politifact|publisher=Politifact|access-date=January 23, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Clark|first=Lesley|title=Frederica Wilson backs Nancy Pelosi \u2013 but not the House hat ban|url=http://miamiherald.typepad.com/nakedpolitics/2010/11/frederica-wilson-backs-nancy-pelosi-but-not-the-house-hat-ban.html|publisher=Miami Herald Blog|date=November 17, 2010|access-date=January 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education, and early career==\nWilson was born '''Frederica Smith''' on November 5, 1942, in [[Miami]], [[Florida]], the daughter of Beulah (n\u00e9e Finley) and Thirlee Smith. Her maternal grandparents were [[The Bahamas|Bahamian]].<ref name=bweekly>{{cite news |first=|last=|title=US Congresswoman Frederica Wilson Courtesy calls on Bahamas' Government |url=http://www.thebahamasweekly.com/publish/bis-news-updates/Courtesy_call_on_National_Security_Minister16497.shtml |work=Bahamas Weekly |publisher= |date=2011-06-20 |access-date=2011-06-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://freepages.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/%7Ebattle/reps/wilsonfrederica.htm|title=Frederica Wilson ancestry|work=ancestry.com|access-date=March 17, 2015}}</ref> Wilson earned her bachelor of arts degree from [[Fisk University]] in 1963,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=W000808|title=Wilson, Frederica|work=Biographical Directory of the United States Congress|publisher=bioguide.congress.gov|access-date=March 17, 2015}}</ref> and her master of arts degree from the [[University of Miami]] in 1972.<ref name=\"Frederica S. Wilson FL\">[http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=17319 Frederica S. Wilson (FL)], Project Vote Smart</ref> She served as the principal of Skyway Elementary School in Miami.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/news/politics/florida-politics-blog/fl-reg-frederica-wilson-five-things-20171020-story.html|title=Frederica Wilson and her fancy hats: Five things you need to know about the congresswoman at war with Trump|last=Sweeney|first=Dan|date=October 20, 2017|work=Sun-Sentinel.com|access-date=October 21, 2017|language=en-US}}</ref> In 1992 she left her position as principal to serve on the [[Miami-Dade County Public Schools|Miami-Dade County School Board]]. While a member of the school board,<ref name=\":0\" /> Wilson started  5000 Role Models of Excellence, an in-school mentoring program.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Florida legislature==\nWilson represented District 104 in the [[Florida House of Representatives]] from 1998 to 2002.<ref name=\":0\" /> She then represented the 33rd District<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.flsenate.gov/data/Publications/Archive/SenateHandbooks/pdf/2002-04%20Handbook.pdf|title=2002-2004 Senate Handbook|last=|first=|date=|website=Florida Senate Website Archive|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2018-04-13}}</ref> in the [[Florida Senate]] from 2002 until her election to Congress in 2010 when term limits prevented her from running again.<ref name=\":0\" /> She served as Minority Leader Pro Tempore in 2006, then Minority Whip.\n\nAn early supporter of [[Barack Obama]]'s [[Barack Obama presidential campaign, 2008|2008 presidential campaign]], she voted for Obama and [[Joe Biden]] in 2008 as one of Florida's [[Electoral College (United States)|presidential electors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5i5uzTpibgiqcSURUWPVvUQRzYSIQD953FPDO0|title=AP: It's official: Barack Obama elected 44th president|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n[[File:Florida-representatives-take-oath-miami-federal-courthouse.jpg|thumb|Chief Judge [[Kevin Michael Moore]], swearing in Members of Congress [[Carlos Curbelo]], Frederica Wilson, [[Mario D\u00edaz-Balart]], and [[Ileana Ros-Lehtinen]]. ''(February 2015)'']]\n\n===2010 election===\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2010#District 17}}\nWhen [[Kendrick Meek]] retired from [[Florida's 17th congressional district]] to run for the [[United States Senate election in Florida, 2010|United States Senate in 2010]], Wilson ran for the [[Florida's 17th congressional district|open seat]] and won the Democratic nomination to take it.<ref>{{cite news | first = Chuck | last = Fadely | title = Frederica Wilson likely headed for 17th district Congressional seat | date = 2010-08-17 | url = http://www.miamiherald.com/508/index.html?media_id=17709643&genre_id=4220 | work = [[Miami Herald]] | access-date = 2010-09-02 | quote = Frederica Wilson dominated a nine-candidate field for the Democratic nomination for the 17th Congressional seat vacated by Kendrick Meek. With no apparent Republican or Conservative opposition in the general election, she will likely go to Washington. She celebrated Tuesday night at the Chef Creole restaurant in Miami Gardens.}}</ref> She won the general election on November 2, 2010, without electoral opposition in a district where the Democratic nomination is [[tantamount to election]].\n\nShe is a member of the [[Congressional Progressive Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Caucus Members|author=|url=https://cpc-grijalva.house.gov/index.cfm?sectionid=71&sectiontree=2,71|format=|publisher=Congressional Progressive Caucus|date=|accessdate=30 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific|Subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space, and Technology|Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Space|Subcommittee on Space and Aeronautics]]\n** [[United States House Science Subcommittee on Technology|Subcommittee on Technology and Innovation]]\n\n===Caucus memberships===\n* [[Congressional Black Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://cbc.house.gov/membership/|format=|publisher=Congressional Black Caucus|date=|accessdate=7 March 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional Arts Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Membership|author=|url=https://artscaucus-slaughter.house.gov/membership|format=|publisher=Congressional Arts Caucus|date=|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n*[[Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Members|author=|url=http://www.ng911institute.org/about-the-congressional-nextgen-9-1-1-caucus|format=|publisher=Congressional NextGen 9-1-1 Caucus|date=|accessdate=14 June 2018}}</ref>\n\n===2012 election===\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2012#District 24}}\n\n===2014 election===\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2014#District 24}}\n\n===2016 election===\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Florida, 2016#District 24}}\n\n===Tenure===\n;Education\nDuring her career as an educator, she founded the 5000 Role Models program, which seeks to bring down dropout rates. Since her time in the Florida legislature, she has strongly opposed standardized testing.<ref name=\"Wilson Post\">{{cite news|title=Frederica Wilson (D-Fla.)|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/frederica-wilson-d-fla/gIQA8EKXKP_topic.html#t-a-glance|series=''WhoRunsGov''|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106223226/http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/frederica-wilson-d-fla/gIQA8EKXKP_topic.html|archive-date=November 6, 2013|access-date=January 7, 2017|publisher=Washington Post}}</ref> She has expressed concern with the [[Florida Comprehensive Assessment Test]] (FCAT), suggesting that the funds spent administering the standardized test would be better spent on improving education by hiring more teachers, and proposing in 2012 that tutoring companies be banned from exploiting vulnerable children, \"even if it means banning companies like Ignite! Learning, founded by ex-Governor [[Jeb Bush]]'s brother, Neil\".<ref name=FCAT>{{cite news|last=Wilson|first=Frederica|title=FCAT closes door for many students|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2012-04-15/news/fl-wilson-oped0415-20120415_1_fcat-students-graduate-high-school-diploma|newspaper=Sun Sentinel|date=April 15, 2012|access-date=January 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Tea Party\nFrederica Wilson has taken a vocal opposition to the [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]]. At a Miami town hall meeting in 2011, she told citizens to remember that the Tea Party is the real enemy and that they hold Congress hostage. She expressed her belief that they had one goal in mind: \"to make President Obama a one-term president.\"<ref name=Enemy>{{cite news|title=Dem Congresswoman: 'The Real Enemy Is The Tea Party' [video]|url=http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2011/08/23/dem_congresswoman_the_real_enemy_is_the_tea_party.html|website=Real Clear Politics|date=August 23, 2011}}</ref>\n\n;Trayvon Martin case\nWilson took a vocal stance in the death of [[Trayvon Martin]], who was a constituent of hers and whose family she says she has known all her life. She has been both praised and criticized for stating shortly after the killing the motive of the accused, [[George Zimmerman]], was racism. She suggested in March 2012 that Zimmerman had \"hunted\" Martin, based simply on his race.<ref name=\"Lawmakers blast\">{{cite news|title=Democratic lawmakers blast police in teen killing|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-florida-shooting-congress-idUSBRE82Q0W520120328|last=Smith|first=Donna|publisher=Reuters|date=March 28, 2012|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref> She said, \"Mr. Zimmerman should be arrested immediately for his own safety.\"<ref name=\"wilson1\"/><ref name=\"wilson2\"/>\n\nIn March 2012, in a statement on the floor of the House of Representatives, Wilson said, \"Justice must be served. No more racial profiling!\"<ref name=\"Calls for Justice\">{{cite news|title=Fla. Rep. Frederica Wilson Calls for Justice on House Floor for Trayvon Martin [Video]|url=http://colorlines.com/archives/2012/03/fla_rep_frederica_wilson_calls_for_justice_on_house_floor_for_trayvon_martin_video.html|newspaper=Color Lines|last=Rivas|first=Jorge|date=March 21, 2012|at=Quote occurs at approximately 3 minutes, 11 seconds|access-date=January 6, 2012}}</ref> Describing the incident as a \"classic example of racial profiling quickly followed by murder\", she called for Zimmerman to be arrested.<ref name=\"Call for more action\">{{cite news|title=Trayvon Martin shooting spurs lawmakers to call for more action|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/8301-503544_162-57401689-503544/trayvon-martin-shooting-spurs-lawmakers-to-call-for-more-action/|last=Condon|first=Stephanie|website=CBS News|date=March 21, 2012|access-date=January 6, 2017}}</ref> Wilson organized a rally in Miami on April 1, 2012, calling for Zimmerman's imprisonment. She criticized Florida's self-defense gun law, the so-called \"Stand Your Ground\" law, in the wake of Martin's killing, even though she voted for it as a legislator. She expressed her feeling that when new laws go on the books that work against the people, the laws \"should be looked at and repealed.\"<ref name=\"Nix self-defense law\">{{cite news|last=Dixon|first=Darius|title=Trayvon Martin shooting: Frederica Wilson wants to nix Florida's self-defense gun law|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0312/74301.html|newspaper=Politico|date=March 21, 2012}}</ref> In April 2012, Wilson said that the death of Martin was \"definitely\" murder.<ref name=\"Says definitely murder\">{{cite news|title=Trayvon\u2019s death was murder, Congressman Frederica Wilson says |url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/04/03/2729373/trayvons-death-was-murder-congresswoman.html |newspaper=The Miami Herald |date=April 4, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605064317/http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/04/03/2729373/trayvons-death-was-murder-congresswoman.html |archivedate=2012-06-05 |df= }}</ref> However, on July 13, 2013, a jury acquitted Zimmerman of the charges of second degree murder and manslaughter.<ref name=\"acquit\">{{cite news|last=Campo |first=Arian |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424127887324879504578603562762064502?mod=WSJ_hpp_LEFTTopStories |title=Jury Acquits Zimmerman of All Charges |work=The Wall Street Journal|date=July 14, 2013|accessdate=September 17, 2013}}</ref>\n\nConcern was raised about Wilson's outspoken comments, with some asking if her rhetoric was \"making it more difficult for the prosecutor to do her job.\"<ref name=\"Martin Transcript\">{{cite news|title=Rhetoric On Trayvon Martin Intensifies |url=http://transcripts.cnn.com/TRANSCRIPTS/1203/28/cnr.02.html|newspaper=CNN|series=Transcripts|date=March 28, 2012}}</ref> Wilson has been calling for tougher laws to prevent racial profiling.<ref name=\"Prohibit profiling\">{{cite news|title=Rep. Frederica Wilson calls for tougher laws to prohibit racial profiling|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/2012/04/17/2753948/rep-frederica-wilson-calls-for.html|newspaper=The Miami Herald|date=April 17, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Anti-hazing\n{{further|List of hazing deaths in the United States}}\nWilson led efforts to combat bullying and [[hazing]] both as the South Atlantic Regional Director for [[Alpha Kappa Alpha]] Sorority and as a member of Congress.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://wilson.house.gov/common/popup/popup.cfm?action=item.print&itemID=189|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121224213742/http://wilson.house.gov/common/popup/popup.cfm?action=item.print&itemID=189|archive-date=December 24, 2012|title=Congresswoman Wilson to Introduce Federal Anti-Hazing Bill in January|date=December 27, 2011|series=[press release]|publisher=United States House of Representatives. wilson.house.gov}}</ref> A Miami Herald reporter nicknamed her \"The Haze Buster\" for her public stance against hazing. She was part of a coalition of African-American fraternity and sorority leaders who launched an anti-hazing campaign after the 2011 death of Florida A&M drum major [[List of hazing deaths in the United States#2010s|Robert Champion]] Jr.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2012/05/31/black-groups-launch-anti-hazing-campaign/ | work=Fox News | title=Black groups launch anti-hazing campaign | date=May 31, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Recognition\nMSNBC's \"The Grio\", an African-American news and opinion platform, named Wilson to \"The Grio 100\" for 2012.<ref name=\"The Grio 2012\">{{cite news|title=The Grio 2012|url=http://video.msnbc.msn.com/the-grio/46397430#46397430|newspaper=MSNBC}}</ref>\n\n;Shooting of Charles Kinsey\n{{Main|Shooting of Charles Kinsey}}\nAfter the release of the video showing police shooting mental health therapist Charles Kinsey in her district, Wilson tweeted in July 2016 that she was shocked and angered by Kinsey's shooting. She added that \"Like everyone else I have one question: Why?\"<ref name=\"ortiz\">{{cite news|last1=Ortiz|first1=Eric|title=Cops Shoot Unarmed Caregiver With His Hands Up While He Helps Man|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/cops-shoot-unarmed-caregiver-charles-kinsey-his-hands-while-he-n614106|access-date=July 21, 2016|publisher=NBC News|date=July 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;Death of Sgt. La David Johnson\nFollowing the death of Sgt. La David Johnson on October 4, 2017, in an [[2017 Tongo Tongo ambush|attack in Niger]], Wilson told the press that on October 16, 2017, President Trump had called Johnson's widow while she was on the way to Miami International Airport for the arrival of Johnson\u2019s remains. In the car with her were Johnson's mother and other family members, as well as Wilson, a long-time friend of the family.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shear|first=Michael D.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/19/us/politics/john-kelly-son-trump.html|title=\u2018Kelly Delivers Fervent Defense of Trump Call to Soldier\u2019s Widow|publisher=The New York Times|date=October 19, 2017 | access-date=October 21, 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Phillips|first=Kristine|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/checkpoint/wp/2017/10/18/fallen-sgt-la-david-johnson-caught-in-trump-call-controversy-was-a-family-oriented-soldier/|title= The private life of Sgt. La David Johnson, the slain soldier ensnared in a Trump controversy|work=Washington Post|date=October 18, 2017 | access-date=October 19, 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=\"McC\">{{cite web |last=McCaskill|first=Roland|url= http://www.politico.com/story/2017/10/19/john-kelly-frederica-wilson-trump-243956 |title=Kelly emotionally defends Trump\u2019s call to military widow|publisher=Politico|date=October 19, 2017 | access-date=October 20, 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Cohen|first=Howard|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/local/community/miami-dade/miami-gardens/article179433356.html|title=\u2018He knew what he signed up for,\u2019 Trump reportedly tells widow of fallen Miami Gardens soldier|publisher=The Miami Herald|date=October 17, 2017 | access-date=October 21, 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Abramson|first=Alana|url=http://time.com/4987321/sgt-la-david-t-johnson-remains/|title=David T. Johnson's Widow Received His Remains|publisher=TIME|date=October 18, 2017 | access-date=October 21, 2017 |quote=}}</ref>  The widow put the call on speakerphone so that Wilson and others in the car heard it. Wilson stated Trump \"was almost like joking\" and that he said \"he (La David) knew what he signed up for, but I guess it still hurt\".  Trump later called Wilson's characterization of the conversation a \"fabrication.\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Hawkins|first=Derek|url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2017/10/19/rep-frederica-wilson-didnt-flinch-at-trumps-attacks-her-record-explains-why/?tid=a_inl |title=Rep. Frederica Wilson didn\u2019t flinch at Trump\u2019s attacks. Her record explains why.|publisher=New York Times|date=October 19, 2017 | access-date=October 20, 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref name=\"imbroglio\">{{cite web |last1=Landler|first1=Mark|last2=Alcindor|first2=Yamiche|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2017/10/18/us/politics/trump-widow-johnson-call.html?emc=edit_th_20171019&nl=todaysheadlines&nlid=71493482 |title= Trump\u2019s Condolence Call to Soldier's Widow Ignites an Imbroglio|work=New York Times|date=October 18, 2017 | access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref> Johnson's mother confirmed Wilson's account on October 18,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Gearan|first1=Anne|last2=Phillips|first2=Kristine|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/post-politics/wp/2017/10/18/totally-fabricated-trump-disputes-congresswomans-depiction-of-his-exchange-with-soldiers-widow/|title= Fallen soldier\u2019s mother: 'Trump did disrespect my son'|work=Washington Post|date=October 18, 2017 | access-date=October 19, 2017 |quote=}}</ref> at which point the White House ceased disputing Wilson's account of the phone call and instead claimed that she was \"mischaracterizing the spirit\" of the conversation.<ref name=\"imbroglio\"/> On October 23, Johnson's widow also confirmed Wilson's account.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Phillips|first1=Kristine|last2=Freedom du Lac|first2=J.|last3=Siegel|first3=Rachel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/politics/wp/2017/10/23/it-made-me-cry-gold-star-widow-myeshia-johnson-breaks-silence-on-trumps-condolence-call/|title=Gold Star widow Myeshia Johnson said Trump stumbled recalling her husband's name|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=2017-10-23|accessdate=2017-10-25}}</ref>\n\nOn October 19, 2017, [[White House Chief of Staff]] [[John F. Kelly]] gave a press briefing at the White House. Kelly, who is a [[wikt:gold star parent|gold star parent]] and was present at Trump's end during the phone conversation, did not deny that Trump said the words reported.<ref name=\"McC\"/> But he defended Trump's comments \"forcefully and emotionally\", saying that Trump \"in his way tried to express that opinion that he\u2019s a brave man, a fallen hero.\"<ref name=\"McC\"/> He also attacked Wilson for having listened to the phone call and falsely claimed she had a \"history of politicizing what should be sacred moments\", citing the 2015 dedication of an FBI field office in Miami as an example. He claimed that her speech at that ceremony was \"about how she was instrumental in getting the funding for that building\" from then-President Barack Obama.<ref name=\"McC\"/>\n\nKelly's statement was disproven by the video recording of the event.<ref Name=\"video\">{{cite web |last=Nakamura|first=David|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/video-shows-kelly-made-inaccurate-claims-about-congresswoman-in-feud-over-condolence-call/2017/10/20/5cd328e4-b5bf-11e7-be94-fabb0f1e9ffb_story.html?|title= Video shows Kelly made inaccurate claims about lawmaker in feud over Trump\u2019s condolence call|publisher=The Washington Post|date=October 20, 2017 | access-date=October 21, 2017 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.sun-sentinel.com/local/broward/94925992-132.html |title=Full video of Frederica Wilson 2015 speech at new FBI building|publisher=SunSentinel|access-date=October 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=cbsbuilding>{{Cite news|last=CBS News|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/frederica-wilson-fbi-building-john-kelly-trump/|title=Fact-checking the John Kelly-Frederica Wilson controversy|date=October 21, 2017|access-date=October 21, 2017}}</ref> During her nine-minute speech, Wilson spoke for less than three minutes about leading an effort to expedite a bill through congress.  The bill\u2019s purpose was naming the FBI building after two FBI agents slain in the line of duty; the bill would normally not have become law in time for the building\u2019s dedication ceremony.  Wilson dedicated the remainder of her speech to acknowledging other politicians involved in the effort, thanking FBI personnel, and talking about the slain agents.<ref name=\"ap_fact_check\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-20/ap-fact-check-kelly-distorts-tale-in-slamming-congresswoman|title=AP Fact Check: Kelly Distorted Facts in Attack on Congresswoman|date=2017-10-20|work=Bloomberg.com|access-date=2017-10-23}}</ref><ref name=\"politifact201017\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/statements/2017/oct/20/john-kelly/fact-checking-john-kelly-frederica-wilsons-2015-sp/|title=Fact-checking John Kelly on Frederica Wilson's 2015 speech|work=@politifact|access-date=2017-10-23|language=en}}</ref> The FBI secured the building's funding in 2009, before Wilson became a congresswoman in 2011.<ref name=cbsbuilding/> ''[[The Miami Herald]]'' reported that Kelly had misquoted the cost of the building as $20 million versus the actual $194 million.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Daugherty|first1=Alex|last2=Kumar|first2=Anita|last3=Hanks|first3=Douglas|title=In attack on Frederica Wilson over Trump\u2019s call to widow, John Kelly gets facts wrong|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/national-politics/article179869321.html|work=[[The Miami Herald]]|accessdate=25 October 2017}}</ref> As a result, several newspapers have called for Kelly to apologize to Wilson.<ref>{{Cite web|last=Editorial Board|title=John Kelly owes the congresswoman an apology|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/john-kelly-owes-the-congresswoman-an-apology/2017/10/20/c81205e2-b5c1-11e7-9e58-e6288544af98_story.html?|website=The Washington Post|date=October 21, 2017|access-date=October 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Editorial|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/opinion/john-kelly-mistake-owes-apology-rep-frederica-wilson-article-1.3577709|title=John Kelly\u2019s mistake: He owes an apology to Rep. Frederica Wilson|work=NY Daily News|date=October 20, 2017|access-date=October 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Sun Sentinel Editorial Board|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/opinion/editorials/fl-op-editorial-john-kelly-fredrica-wilson-20171020-story.html|title=Frederica Wilson is no 'empty barrel,' John Kelly {{!}} Editorial|work=Sun Sentinel|date=October 20, 2017|access-date=October 21, 2017}}</ref>  The White House said the video did not capture all of Wilson's comments.<ref name=\"wh_quote\">{{Cite news|last=Sampathkumar|first=Mythili|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/us-politics/trump-john-kelly-questions-inappropriate-white-house-sarah-huckabee-sanders-soldier-widow-a8012186.html |title=White House says its 'highly inappropriate' to question Trump's chief of staff because he is a four-star general|date=October 20, 2017|work=Independent|access-date=October 24, 2017|quote='She [Sanders] also said the Congresswoman \"had quite a few comments that day that weren't part of that speech and weren't part of that video that were also witnessed by many people that were there \u2014 what Gen. Kelly referenced yesterday\".'}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nWilson is widowed. She has three children.<ref name=\"Frederica S. Wilson FL\" /> Wilson is an avid wearer of hats. She has a large collection that includes hundreds of hats of all different varieties. She wears one every day. During the tenure of former [[List of Speakers of the United States House of Representatives|House Speaker]] [[John Boehner]], she unsuccessfully asked him to waive the rule which prohibits the wearing of hats on the floor of the House of Representatives, a rule in place since 1837.<ref name=Politifact />\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin|title=2010 17th congressional district of Florida Democratic primary election<ref>[http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/house/florida/17 Florida 17th District Profile] ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Frederica Wilson\n |votes = '''16,653'''\n |percentage = '''35%'''\n |change = }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = [[Rudy Moise]]\n |votes = 7,769\n |percentage = 16%\n |change = }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = [[Shirley Gibson]]\n |votes = 5,777\n |percentage = 12%\n |change = }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = [[Yolly Roberson]]\n |votes = 4,921\n |percentage = 10%\n |change = }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = [[Phillip Brutus]]\n |votes = 4,068\n |percentage = 8%\n |change = }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Marleine Bastien\n |votes = 2,889\n |percentage = 6%\n |change = }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = Scott Galvin\n |votes = 2,653\n |percentage = 6%\n |change = }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = [[James Bush (Florida politician)|James Bush]]\n |votes = 2,630\n |percentage = 5%\n |change = }}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |candidate = [[Andre Williams]]\n |votes = 842\n |percentage = 2%\n |change = }}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin|title=2010 17th congressional district of Florida general election}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n |party = Democratic Party (United States)\n |